You are a senior full-stack engineer and software architect. Build a production-grade, scalable, multi-tenant application security project management platform in Python with MySQL, HTML, Bootstrap, CSS, and JavaScript.

Your task is to design and implement a complete, maintainable, secure, and extensible web application for managing application security work across products, projects, tasks, and findings.

Core objective:
Create a system where users can manage application security programs with flexible GUI-driven form builders, role-based access control, reusable saved form templates, and a customizable dashboard built from database-backed widgets.

Technology stack:
- Backend: Python (use a production-ready web framework such as Django or FastAPI; choose the one best suited for scalability, maintainability, and admin workflows)
- Database: MySQL
- Frontend: HTML5, Bootstrap 5, CSS3, JavaScript
- Use server-side rendering where appropriate, but build interactive UI components where needed
- Prioritize clean architecture, modular design, and long-term maintainability

IMPORTANT AUTHENTICATION AND USER CONTEXT REQUIREMENT:
- Do NOT implement application-level authentication/login/password management.
- The application will run in a trusted enterprise environment.
- The application must automatically identify the currently logged-in operating system or enterprise user from the environment/session/user profile.
- Use the detected OS/domain username as the application identity.
- Supported username formats may include:
  - firstname.lastname
  - firstname.middlename.lastname
  - firstname.lastname.corp
  - firstname.middlename.lastname.corp
- This detected username must be automatically used in:
  - created_by
  - updated_by
  - timestamps
  - audit logs
  - comments
  - activity tracking
  - ownership fields
  - dashboard personalization
- Example:
  - John Smith logged into workstation as john.smith.corp
  - System automatically records:
    - created_by = john.smith.corp
- There should be no login page.
- User identity should be automatically captured from the runtime environment or request context.
- Build the system so future SSO/LDAP/AD integration can be added later without major redesign.

1. Authorization and Role-Based Access Control
Even without application authentication, implement RBAC using detected enterprise usernames.
- Implement role-based access control (RBAC).
- Roles must be assignable to enterprise usernames.
- Support at least these roles:
  - Super Admin
  - Admin
  - Security Manager
  - Project Manager
  - Analyst
  - Viewer
- Permissions must be granular and enforced both in backend and UI.
- Every action must be protected by authorization checks.
- Include an admin screen for mapping enterprise usernames to roles.

2. Core domain structure
Create the following main modules and entities:
- Products
- Projects
- Tasks
- Findings
- Dashboard
- Form Builder / Template Builder
- Roles and Permissions
- Audit Logs

3. Flexible GUI-driven form design
Users must be able to design forms from the GUI without code.
- Allow creating and editing custom forms for:
  - Projects
  - Tasks
  - Findings
- Support common field types:
  - text
  - textarea
  - number
  - date
  - datetime
  - dropdown/select
  - multi-select
  - checkbox
  - radio
  - file upload
  - user/assignee selector
  - status selector
  - tags
- Support field properties:
  - required/optional
  - label
  - placeholder
  - default value
  - validation rules
  - help text
  - display order
  - visibility rules
  - read-only rules
  - conditional logic if feasible
- Form layouts must be configurable from the UI.
- Designed forms must be saved in the database as reusable templates.
- Templates must be reusable across other projects, tasks, and findings.
- Version form templates so that future edits do not break historical records.

4. Reusable saved form templates
- Persist form definitions, field definitions, layout configuration, and validation metadata in MySQL.
- Allow users with permissions to clone, reuse, edit, version, archive, and restore templates.
- Templates should be assignable to different product/project contexts.
- Instances of forms must store submitted data separately from the template definition.

5. Dashboard customization
Build a dashboard that users can customize from the GUI.
- Users can add/remove/reorder widgets.
- Dashboard widgets must be configurable from data stored in the database.
- All saved entities and structured data should be available for dashboard visualization.
- Support widgets such as:
  - counts
  - status breakdowns
  - SLA/aging metrics
  - recent activity
  - open findings
  - task progress
  - project health
  - overdue items
  - trend charts if feasible
- Users should be able to configure widget filters and data source scope.
- Dashboard layout should be saved per user or per role, depending on permissions.

6. Application security workflow
Model the application security lifecycle in a practical way.
- Products can contain multiple projects.
- Projects can contain multiple tasks.
- Findings can be linked to projects, tasks, and optionally products.
- Add typical security metadata such as severity, priority, status, assignee, due date, remediation status, verification state, and comments.
- Allow traceability and history of changes.
- Include audit trails for create/update/delete actions.

7. Data model and persistence
Design a normalized MySQL schema with:
- Users (enterprise usernames only, no passwords)
- Roles
- Permissions
- User-role mapping
- Products
- Projects
- Tasks
- Findings
- Custom form templates
- Form fields
- Form submissions / values
- Dashboard layouts
- Dashboard widgets
- Comments / activity logs
- Audit logs
- Attachments if needed
- Status/history tables if needed
- Ensure the schema supports future extension without major redesign

8. API and UI expectations
- Build a clean, usable frontend.
- Use Bootstrap for layout and responsiveness.
- Keep the UI professional and enterprise-ready.
- Build create/read/update/delete flows for all core entities.
- Include search, filtering, sorting, and pagination.
- Include empty states, validation messages, and user-friendly error handling.
- Support reusable components and consistent page layouts.

9. Security and production quality
- Since there is no application authentication, ensure enterprise user context cannot be spoofed easily.
- Use trusted request/session/environment identity sources.
- Protect against CSRF, XSS, SQL injection, and common web vulnerabilities.
- Validate all inputs on both frontend and backend.
- Use parameterized queries or ORM safely.
- Add structured error handling and logging.
- Ensure the system is production-ready, not a demo.
- Include an audit trail for sensitive operations.
- Use environment-based configuration.

10. Scalability and maintainability
- Follow a modular architecture.
- Separate concerns clearly: models, services, controllers/routes, templates, static assets, utilities.
- Make the codebase easy to extend with new form field types and new dashboard widgets.
- Avoid hardcoding business rules where configuration is better.
- Structure code so the application can scale to many products, projects, tasks, and findings.

Implementation guidance:
- Choose a framework and explain the choice briefly in code comments or README.
- Prefer ORM-based database access.
- Use migrations for schema management.
- Use reusable components for forms, widgets, tables, and modals.
- Keep JavaScript lightweight and focused on interactivity.
- Use clean, professional styling with Bootstrap and custom CSS.
- Ensure the app runs locally with clear setup instructions.

Deliverables:
1. Complete source code for the application.
2. Database schema and migrations.
3. Seed data for initial roles, permissions, and example records.
4. Working UI for:
   - dashboard
   - product management
   - project management
   - task management
   - finding management
   - form builder
   - dashboard builder
   - admin/RBAC management
5. README with setup, configuration, database setup, and run instructions.
6. A short architecture overview and notes on how the form builder and dashboard builder work.

Important design principles:
- Keep the system generic enough for future application security use cases.
- Make the form builder and dashboard builder data-driven and reusable.
- Persist all user-designed structures in the database.
- Ensure permissions determine what users can see and edit.
- Build with production quality, not a proof of concept.
- Ensure enterprise usernames are consistently tracked in all records and audit events.

Acceptance criteria:
- The application automatically identifies the enterprise/OS logged-in user.
- A user only accesses modules allowed by RBAC permissions.
- A user can create a custom form in the GUI for projects, tasks, or findings.
- A designed form can be saved and reused in later projects/tasks/findings.
- A user can customize a dashboard and save it.
- Dashboard widgets read from database-backed entities and filters.
- All core entities are manageable through a professional web UI.
- Audit logs consistently capture enterprise usernames and timestamps.
- The system is secure, scalable, and cleanly structured.

Before coding, produce a concise implementation plan, proposed folder structure, data model outline, and key design decisions. Then implement the application in a way that is immediately runnable.